      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The concept of substantive due process has been powerfully utilized to protect fundamental rights, most notably in cases establishing a right to privacy, such as *Griswold v. Connecticut*. This ruling recognized a zone of personal liberty protected from government intrusion, which has since been expanded to protect reproductive rights and personal decisions. Furthermore, the doctrine has been essential in challenging discriminatory laws, reinforcing the idea that certain liberties are inherent and cannot be legislated away by a government.",
      "source": "target",
